            <p>The article is very interesting and aims to present the fascinating xFORMAL project within a broader theoretical framework. The article has very good potential, and I think it needs to be improved in some points.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The first three parts offer indeed a broad view of the cultural and political foundations at international level on which the EU-funded xFORMAL project is based. The first section is definitely the most interesting and valuable part of the essay. I really appreciated the comprehensive overview of recent actions made by international bodies for culture and education. It is an excellent summary, very useful for contextualising the project, but which can also be helpful to anyone interested in the topic.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The bibliography on pilgrimage, tourism and ecomuseums is also correct and appropriate, though brief in relation to the vast number of texts published recently on these topics. However, as this is a work of an international scope, it would be preferable to present broader examples and comparisons. For example, among the reproductions of the Holy Land conceived as alternatives to the routes to Jerusalem, the experience of Verona Minor Hierusalem is very interesting and could be better contextualised by looking at the numerous examples worldwide (see Crispin Paine's most recent bibliography).</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> I find that the second part of the article needs revision. First of all, what is presented as an xFORMAL case study does not seem to be a case study, nor is it clear whether it describes a finished work or a proposal. The description of a real scenario would really give strength to the essay.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In dealing with these themes, however, the authors should better frame the issues of gamification in heritage tourism and learning practices. I suggest looking at further bibliography such as "Tourism Fictions, Simulacra and Virtualities", edited by Maria Gravari-Barbas, Nelson Graburn and Jean-Fran&#x00e7;ois Staszak, Routledge 2020.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Similarly, when discussing citizen engagement through digital and virtual, it is important to mention themes of digital tools for heritage (i.e. equality of access to devices, right to disconnection, digital fatigue and digital exclusion). These are key issues, , deeply debated in contemporary museology and heritage use, that cannot be overlooked.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> At last, I have some concerns regarding the use of &#x2018;pilgrimage&#x2019; in this case. The word 'pilgrimage' (although always defined in the article as 'cultural pilgrimage') is always strongly characterised by religious aspects. In this text, the concept of pilgrimage is applied to non-religious (and pre-Roman) matters, but this is not always obvious to the reader. I suggest to the authors to clarify very well what they mean by the word &#x2018;pilgrimage&#x2019;, and to reflect on the fact that this word do not fit in discourses that focus only on the monuments and places, without entering into the central issue of any &#x201c;pilgrimage&#x201d;, that is the individual, supernatural perception of the place, as experienced by every single visitor.</p>
            <p>Is the case presented with sufficient detail to be useful for teaching or other practitioners?</p>
            <p>Partly</p>
            <p>Is the work clearly and accurately presented and does it cite the current literature?</p>
            <p>Yes</p>
            <p>If applicable, is the statistical analysis and its interpretation appropriate?</p>
            <p>Not applicable</p>
            <p>Are all the source data underlying the results available to ensure full access and reuse by other researchers?</p>
            <p>Partly</p>
            <p>Are the conclusions drawn adequately supported by the data and analysis?</p>
            <p>Partly</p>
            <p>Is the background of the case&#x2019;s history and progression described in sufficient detail?</p>
            <p>Partly</p>
            <p>Reviewer Expertise:</p>
            <p>Cultural Heritage, Museums, Christian Archaeology</p>
            <p>I confirm that I have read this submission and believe that I have an appropriate level of expertise to confirm that it is of an acceptable scientific standard, however I have significant reservations, as outlined above.</p>
