            <p>The paper presents the project xFormal that aims to test and improve informal or non-formal learning on Cultural Heritage related to the pre-Roman European history, through the use of game-based technologies.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The paper is well-structured into two main parts, after the introduction. The first one is devoted to the presentation of the xFormal project and its theoretical framework, and the second one is focused on the introduction of the cultural-historical game pathways that xFormal project will developed to promote learning in the pre-Roman cultures.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The theoretical framework of the project is very well-written, grounded and easy to understand. It is also well-balanced in the presentation of the main research areas related to the study: (1) Heritage education, (2) Heritage Tourism and cultural pilgrimage, and (3) Education 4.0 and Informal Education that, on the whole, offer a brief but really well-explained review of three fundamental areas in which the project is being developed.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> However, the second part of the structure, the case study could be better introduced and discussed in relation to the theoretical framework previously presented. First of all, it is not clear to what extent the case study has already been implemented or if it is a proposal to be developed, currently. In fact, the case study lacks any reference to the real pathway scenarios that have been selected to its development or a discussion about the results in relation the evaluation systems they are said to be implemented. In addition, in this second part of the article there are some repetitions in relation to the information presented in different sections that make the reader wonder if so many sub-sections are needed or if some of them should be joined (i.e. The Pathway-scenarios + Educational kit (already presented at the end of the previous section); Narrative + Unlocking necessary educational tools).</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> As in the introduction of the article and in the theoretical framework of the project is given importance to the implication of community in writing its own history, I would recommend the authors to explain how the design of the game, pathways-scenarios, and narratives face that aspect. Does the project propose any co-creative experience in the selection and/or design of scenarios and narratives? If so, how was that process implemented or is it being implemented?</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Another important aspect that both the introduction and theoretical framework point to is universal accessibility, and inclusive design. In fact, it is also point out in the conclusions of the article, but there is a complete lack of information regarding this aspect in the presentation of the case study.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> In my opinion, it is important that the article discusses in the Conclusion how the case study proposed can achieve or has already achieved the challenges presented in the introduction and theoretical framework. This could be faced with a broader discussion in the conclusions, with more clear and direct relations in between the main points of the theoretical framework, the challenges exposed, and the solutions presented in the case study.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Other points to be considered by the authors are the following:</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 1.The first part of the title (Playing with the cultural pilgrimage to stimulate tourism) should be reconsidered as it does not match its content properly. The article presents a particular project which is more focused on testing new forms of informal education on Cultural Heritage through game-based technologies than on stimulating tourism. The article presents the cultural-historical game pathways, the game ingredients and aims in relation to estimated learning competences, so the main focus in this article is mainly on education, but not on a tourist approach.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 2.&#x00a0;While the plain language summary is well-written and clear, the abstract could be improved in particular in what respect to the main aim of the article, the case study, to which only a sentence is devoted at the end of the abstract. It could also be improved the way in which the structure of the article is presented and a brief reference to the results.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 3. In the whole text there are some excerpts of external authors that are quote with simple quotation marks and others with double quotation marks. I suggest the authors to use a common way for the quotations. For instance, in the paragraph number 8 of the introduction, we find the following two excerpts: &#x2026;
                <bold>"</bold>highlighting the role of education and interpretation of cultural heritage to promote appreciation and respect for cultural diversity
                <bold>"</bold>&#x2026; (double quotation marks)</p>
            <p> &#x2026;
                <bold>&#x2018;</bold>the conservation, safeguarding and transmission of shared values and know-how to future generations
                <bold>&#x2019;</bold>. (simple quotation marks)</p>
            <p> This issue should be reviewed in the whole article.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 4.&#x00a0;In case of long quotations (more than three lines) such as the ones of the Introduction (Paragraph 10, 
                <italic>Europe&#x2019;s rich cultural heritage and dynamic cultural and creative sectors&#x2026;</italic>) and Education 4.0 and Informal education (Paragraph 12, 
                <italic>a lifelong learning process, whereby each&#x2026;</italic>), I will recommend the authors to include them as a separate paragraph, indented and in italic type, without quotation marks.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> 5.&#x00a0;There is a minor mistake in paragraph 4 of the Introduction:</p>
            <p> 
