            <p>The article presents a case study of the construction of the game xFORMAL as a technological tool to create an informal way of accessing the cultural heritage. It is an interesting topic and it has been nice to read the study. Despite that, in my opinion, it should be improved for indexing.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The paper lacks an appropriate theoretical background, since it does not present the main literature review about gamification in tourism, cultural heritage enhancement through technology, and informal learning. I think also that, in order to enhance the role of culture for stimulating tourism (as the authors recall in the title), they should devote more attention to the tourism sector. More theoretical explanations are necessary about the use of technologies in tourism experience, the main drivers and features of experience in tourism, and the role of culture in stimulating tourism. The link between tourism and the aim of the project (and the game) should be made clearer starting from the introduction section. In this section, authors could be more effective also avoiding confusion between the global and European level of analysis: they should focus to a wider and international level (UNESCO), and then to the Europe level, without mixing them.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> The empirical part of the study, devoted to the xFORMAL game, should better reflect the theoretical framework of the study, in order to allow to the readers to understand how the game is able to improve the informal education and to enhance the heritage tourism through the use of technology. More information on the game (where it has been tested, how the games and landscapes have been selected, what is the level of appreciation) could be useful to the readers.</p>
            <p> </p>
            <p> Conclusion should be better linked to the results that arises from the read of the game through the theoretical framework.</p>
